Ludic Pedagogy in Post-Secondary Language Arts 

**According to recent U.S. studies, approximately 97% of boys under 18 and 94% of girls under 18 play video games on a regular basis, spending on average 10,000 hours playing by age 21—often more than the total hours they spend in the middle school and high school classroom combined (****McGonigal, 2011). **This trend extends beyond children and young adults, with the average age of “gamers” at 35, and includes traditional console-based games (Playstation, Xbox, Wii, etc.), online and software-based computer games, and games played on portable devices and mobile phones.

Though often derided as a waste of time, learning science research has demonstrated that successful video games in fact incorporate effective, recursive learning principles. According to James Paul Gee in *What Video Games Teach Us about Learning and Literacy* (2007), games provide learners with:

- active, critical learning, and literary practices

- opportunities to try on and practice with new and valuable identities

- intrinsic rewards for learning and practicing

- opportunities to achieve a level of mastery that extends personal confidence

- opportunities to connect texts and embodied experience.

Yet, despite annual game sales of $15-$20 billion in the U.S. alone, an increasing proliferation of platforms and games, and a demographically diverse range of “gamers,” the potential for ludic pedagogy and the application of learning principles that successfully engage players have been largely untapped by post-secondary educators, despite the increasing evidence of the promise and efficacy of these pedagogies and technologies as instruments of teaching and learning.

Studies comparing student responses to lecture and ludic curriculum incorporating the same learning objectives found that “student experiences in the game mode showed increased alertness, increased feelings of being active, increased feelings of involvement and an increased perception of challenge. Flow characteristics [i.e., state of immersion in an activity] revealed boredom during standard lectures but anxiety and flow during game modes. Finally, some evidence of improved attainment was evident” (Grimley et al., 2011).

As Kurt Squire says in *Changing the Game: What Happens When Video Games Enter the Classroom?* (2005) “the important question is not *whether* educators can use games to support learning, but *how* we can use games most effectively as educational tools” (p. 2).

In my sabbatical proposal I set the following primary goals:

- to study emerging learning science theories of effective ludic learning principles (beginning with the work of Gee, Selfe & Hawisher, Shaffer, and Squire);

- to follow this research by surveying current, relevant applications of games in educational settings (beginning with projects by MIT’s Education Arcade, The Games for Learning Institute, and The Institute for the Future);

- to prepare for publication a paper on the application of ludic pedagogy in post-secondary language arts curriculum;

- to use my findings to rethink the way I teach language arts in post-secondary education, with potential results ranging from an initial single assignment or unit to a paradigm shift in my approach to teaching and learning with available and emerging technologies.

Here starts a report on the course of my sabbatical:

