**Ludic Pedagogy**

The focus of my sabbatical has been the study of learning principles in digital games and the meaningful application of these principles in my own post-secondary language arts curriculum design. It is worth noting that the course of this study extended to also include the role of play in learning in a broader sense, not limited to digital games or classroom contexts. I am very happy with the progress I’ve made and will here provide an overview of the learning principles and theories that I have found most influential to my work: 

- Scot Osterweil’s work involving the importance of play in learning, especially **Th****e ****Four Freedoms of Play:**

- **the freedom to experiment**: The player's motivations are entirely intrinsic and personal. The process is open-ended; 

- **the freedom to fail**: Losing is part of the process;

- **the freedom to try on different identities**: Players aren't necessarily limited by their bodies or surrounding physical context;

- **the freedom of effort**: As described in Peter and Iona Opie's classic ethnography of playground culture, children may scramble around in a game of tag, avoiding being caught for twenty minutes, and then suddenly stop and allow themselves to be tagged once they have reached a certain degree of effort or perhaps want to move on to another activity. Intense playground exertion reminds us that play can involve serious, intense concentration (fun can be hard work), but that players need to be free to choose their level of effort. (Osterweil, 2008)

Many of the learning principles that I will examine in this report are grounded within these Four Freedoms. For example, Jim Gee’s “probing principle” and *the freedom to experiment*--to test and rethink hypotheses--are critical to composition as an iterative process, and is facilitated by giving writers the *freedom to fail *by creating a “psychosocial moratorium,” where “learners can take risks in a space where real-world consequences are lowered” (Gee, 2007). 

I have been very fortunate to collaborate with Scot, during and following my sabbatical, designing Xenos-ISLE at the Learning Games Network;

- the work of James Paul Gee, specifically *What Video Games Have to Teach Us About Learning and Literacy* (2007). Gee’s work has been especially valuable because he has identified** learning principles** at work in good video games and examined their application not only for games, but teaching and learning in general. I’ve focused on the following key principles during my curriculum redesign process:

***Design Principle: ****Learning about and coming to appreciate design and design principles is core to the learning experience (p. 41). *

I am especially interested in the design principle for applied language arts (i.e. learning by doing, in an authentic situation). I intend to teach the rhetorical situation—purpose and needs of audience—not only through writing exercises, but through curriculum that requires rhetorical analysis and design across media (see interactive storytelling & Metagame design in section C of this report).

***Semiotic Principle: ****Learning about and coming to appreciate interrelations within and across multiple sign systems (images, words, actions, symbols, artifacts, etc.) as a complex system is core to the learning experience (p. 42).*

Gee describes a semiotic domain as “an area or set of activities where people think, act and value in certain ways” (p. 19) and argues that “people need to be able to learn to be literate in new semiotic domains throughout their lives” (p. 20). Domains are not defined by facts and principles (i.e. content)—instead a domain is “primarily a lived and historically changing set of distinctive social practices. It is in these social practices that ‘content’ is generated, debated and transformed via distinctive ways of thinking, talking, valuing, acting, and, often, reading and writing” (p. 22).

This is why *design *matters, why thinking within a semiotic group (i.e. discourse communities, comprised of individuals with shared interests) to *generate *content matters more than exposure to created content (though I know that oversimplifies things; reading and modeling is necessary to understand how that group thinks, values, creates).

***Semiotic Domains Principle:****** ****Learning involves mastering, at some level, semiotic domains, and being able to participate, at some level, in the affinity group [individuals with a shared interest] or groups connected to them (p. 23-4).*

This includes self-selected domains (i.e. for a Field of Interest unit), but also domains critical to the contexts of any given curriculum. Learners can participate in these domains through, for example, reading/writing blogs, conducting interviews, corresponding with players in the domain, freelance writing, attending/live-streaming conferences, networking through social media, etc. 

***“Psychosocial Moratorium” Principle: ****Learners can take risks is **a** space where real-world consequences are lowered (p. 59).*

This is what Scot Osterweil calls the freedom to fail, and is absolutely critical in the language arts for readers testing hypotheses about texts and for writers exploring novel ideas and forms. One of the primary strategies I intend to employ to foster this kind of environment is to significantly expand spontaneous writing in the classroom, following the Amherst Writers & Artists method of facilitating writing workshops (I was certified in this method in 2006). The AWA method highly values “brand new” work and the vulnerability of a first draft, and encourages exploration and risk-taking. See section c for more about the AWA method.

***Amplification of Input Principle: ****For a little input, learners get a lot of output (p. 60-2).*[^c0][^c1]

In games, the recursive process is a tight spiral, an active feedback loop of hypothesis testing, reflection and learning. So, what can I do to improve the quality and frequency of feedback to students? A few thoughts: 

- as mentioned above, I’ll incorporate spontaneous writing following the AWA method of providing feedback. Feedback is immediate, and sharing is optional; 

- in response to student writing, instead of making comments in the margins and short-letter responses to papers (at the rough draft and final draft stages), I intend to transition to Google Doc comments. This will allow a dialogue, so that students can ask questions about specific comments and describe their revision process. I intend to make this dialogue ongoing and more open-ended than a generally two-draft submission process;

- I plan to significantly rethink my approach to group activities and provide structured opportunities for peer collaboration in and out of the classroom, especially with the use of comment trees in Google Docs. I’d also like to extend the audience and the feedback loop beyond the classroom and academic support (to semiotic domains and affinity groups, for example).

(Cooper, 2011)

***Practice Principle: ****Learners get lots and lots of practice in a context where the practice is not boring (i.e. in a virtual world that is compelling to learners on their own terms and where the learners experience ongoing success). They spend lots of time on task (p. 65-9).*

Practice needs to be playful and exploratory, providing learners with an interesting set of challenges, not an arbitrary (or arbitrary-feeling) set of challenges. Challenges/contexts for practice should be, for example, relevant, applied, self-selected, affinity-related.

***“******Regime of Competence” Principle: ****The learner gets ample opportunity to operate within, but at the outer edge of, his or her resources, so that at those points things are felt as challenging but not “undoable” (p. 67-9).*

Games are very good at this: games are often adaptive to players’ skills, players can often choose the level at which they play, and games can provide multiple pathways through the game that allow for different but still meaningful experiences.

This can be a challenge in the classroom (where instructors often “teach to the middle”). Flow theory is particularly relevant here, where players who aren’t challenged to their ability experience boredom and those who are challenged beyond their ability experience anxiety. The flow state is the sweet spot, where players are challenged in zonal proximity to their skill. How can we better meet the individual? By tightening the feedback loop, by building “multiple” pathways to learning objectives.

***Probing Principle: ****Learning is a cycle of probing the world (doing something); reflecting in and on this action and, on this basis, forming a hypothesis; reprobing the world to test this hypothesis; and then accepting or rethinking the hypothesis** (p. 105).*

I am particularly interested in the promise of systems thinking and design thinking as approaches to hypothesis testing in the language arts. For example, in “systems” like the rhetorical situation, hypotheses about audience can inform a writer’s decisions about both content and form. With meaningful feedback, the practice of writing as an iterative process gives writers the opportunity to probe, reflect, and rethink hypotheses.

***Multiple Routes Principle: ****There are multiple ways to make progress or move ahead. This allows learners to make choices, rely on their own strengths and style of learning and problem solving, while also exploring alternative styles (p. 105).*

This is a best practice in Universal Course Design, one I intend to implement in the coming semester in rethinking curriculum and grading. I plan to provide a number of options for assignments, but to cluster options in a way that does in fact require students to “explore alternative styles.” 

In his Videogames and Learning course at the University of Michigan, Professor Barry Fishman (2012) eschews a percentage-based grading system in favor of a system based on cumulative points. Students not only have significant choice of assignments, but also the “freedom to fail”; if learning objects aren’t satisfactorily met in one project, students can apply lessons learned to another project. 

This approach appears to allow for what game designer Jenova Chen calls “active flow adjustment.” In his MFA thesis *Flow in Games* (2006) [^c2]Chen writes that “In video games, not only can players gain control from the progression, they can also earn it through driving the boat, which is in fact making meaningful choices. So why don't we give the players choices in a video game and let them navigate their Flow experience?”

  

(Chen, 2006)

Though Chen’s vision targets game designers and players, providing “meaningful choices” should be at the core of educators’ design for learning experiences across curricula.

***Situated Meaning Principle: ****The meanings of signs (words, actions, objects, artifacts, symbols, texts, etc.) are situated in embodied experience. Meanings are not general or decontextualized. Whatever generality meanings come to have is discovered bottom up via embodied experiences** (p. 105).*

Gee writes that “in video games meaning (sense, significance) is itself situation specific and embodied” (p. 81) and that “abstraction rises gradually out of the ground of situated meaning and practice and returns there from time to time, or it is meaningless to most human beings“ (p. 87). The same applies to learning in a general sense. So, how to leverage this in post-secondary composition curriculum, for example? Perhaps through task-based learning with authentic rhetorical situations (especially in terms of purpose and audience), and tasks that are intrinsically valuable to the learner, where learners are empowered to engage in semiotic domains and affinity groups of their choice and encouraged to author texts as designers.

***Bottom-up Basic Skills Principle: ****Basic skills are not learned in isolation or out of context; rather, what counts as a basic skill is discovered bottom up by engaging in more and more of the game/domain or games/domains like it. Basic skills are genre elements of a given type of game/domain (p. 142-3). *

This principle reinforces Gee’s situated meaning principle. The challenge here, for instructors, is how to meaningfully support learners across such a diversity of domains. If pedagogy that generalizes skills/genre elements from across domains means teaching and learning out of context, then teaching and learning through models, scenarios, case studies, and authentic rhetorical situations is a promising approach, where principles discovered through situated experiences can then be abstracted and applied, with practice, to new situations/domains.

***Explicit Information On-Demand and Just-in-Time Principle: ****The learner is given explicit information both on demand and just in time, where the learner needs it or just at the point where the information can be best understood and used in practice (p. 142-3).*

This approach sharply contrasts with the idea of “front-loading” and decontextualized teaching and learning, lending itself to learning by doing and to lab-based curriculum. This principle can be further leveraged when instructors can provide both face to face and virtual support, when peers are empowered (encouraged, networked, recognized) to work collaboratively, and when student support services and engagement with affinity groups are fundamentally integrated into the course experience. 

- Kurt Squire’s research and experience using commercial and educational games and design curriculum in the classroom, especially his 2011 book *Video Games and Learning: Teaching and Participatory Culture in the Digital Age*. Squire’s work on **systemic thinking **prompted me to examine central systems and principles in post-secondary language arts, especially composition courses, including systems within: 

- the rhetorical situation (ethos, pathos, logos; Rogerian argument, etc)

- visual rhetoric and visual literacy

- digital literacy

- stasis theory

- writing as an iterative, recursive process

- collective intelligence, semiotic domains, affinity spaces, and epistemic frames. [^c3]

Squire describes various **game mechanics** that can inform the design of a student-centered learning experience, including:

- Orchestrating time: providing players/learners with short-, medium-, and long-range goals;

- Providing overlapping goals;

- Creating possibility spaces that can provide transformative experiences;

- Constructing open-ended problems (p. 15);[^c4]

	

	Squire also calls for:

 

- “Interest-driven learning, differentiated learning trajectories, multiple levels of expertise, collaboration and competition, and learning through design...” (p. 59);

- “unpacking students’ interests and extending them into new academic domains” (p. 59);

- “mechanisms for students to identify their skills and passions, refine them, and channel them into productive future selves” (p. 62);

- Critical digital literacy that requires “knowing the difference between a diary and front-page story (just like distinguishing between a news story and an editorial). Every site is a unique mix of information with varying degrees of formality, credibility and sanction. Being literate means understanding what content belongs where as well as the relative credence of information in each context” (p. 64);

- situated learning--“It’s difficult to comprehend specialized texts until you’ve been immersed in situations where they are useful” (p. 155).

- **Flow theory**. In *Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience *(1990), Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi argues that a pleasing state of ‘flow’ occurs when one has “a sense that one’s skills are adequate to cope with the challenge at hand, in a goal-directed, rule-bound action system that provides clear clues as to how well one is performing. Concentration is so intense that there is no attention left over to think about anything irrelevant, or to think about problems. Self-consciousness disappears, and the sense of time becomes distorted. An activity that produces such experiences is so gratifying that people are willing to do it for its own sake” (p. 71). 

[^c5]

(Csikszentmihalyi, 1990, p.74) 

A one-size-fits-all educational model simply cannot cultivate this kind of flow state across populations of learners with diverse skills and goals, especially within didactic models that provide limited, delayed feedback from a single, authoritarian audience--the instructor. Instead, curriculum designed to optimally engage students should provide: challenges that are open-ended instead of deficit-based, for learners across skill bases; course goals that are filtered through learner-identified interests and needs, including short, medium, long-range, and overlapping goals (Squire, 2011); and “amplified feedback” through multiple mechanisms from a diverse audience of peers and professionals.

Good digital games use leveling, feedback, power-ups and other mechanics to cultivate flow states in players. As Squire notes, “in a good game, the action is difficult, but players feel that they know what they did wrong or right (sufficient feedback) and that they have the tools to do better next time” (p. 147). I intend to continue to explore the adaptability of these mechanics for teaching and learning in the classroom.

- **constructionism and constructivism, **where learners should be enabled not only to construct their own knowledge systems (Piaget), but to manifest that cognitive process through production that is visible and sharable (Papert). **Problem-based curriculum **designed to produce artifacts of learning is one approach, where a central problem drives student-centered, self-directed activity, where learning happens individually and within small groups, and where teachers provide on-demand and just-in-time guidance as facilitators (learning apprenticeships). According to P. C. Honebein (1996), constructivist collaborative learning environments should: “encourage students to take responsibility for their learning, including what and how they learn; provide multiple perspectives; create self-awareness of the learning process; make learning relevant and authentic; make learning a collaborative and interactive social experience; and use multiple modes of representation and rich media” (qtd. in Whitton and Hollins, 2008). 

- Constructivist theory has been especially relevant in the way I have begun to focus on curriculum focused on fostering systemic thinking and design thinking through **situated learning **that encourages authentic discourse within student-chosen semiotic domains. When activities are anchored in authentic situations, “learning in ‘mindful’ ways results in knowledge that is considered meaningful and useful, as compared to the ‘inert’ knowledge that results from decontextualized learning strategies (such as traditional classroom worksheets)” (Rieber, 1996, p.11). 

As Klopfer notes, “we do not learn to read and write generically, but rather we learn to read and write in specific contexts. That is, our language is specific to the topic, content, audience and place of communication” (2008, p. 175). Situated learning, as opposed to abstracted activities, provides the experience necessary to learn deeply. As Gee states: “The human mind works best when it can build and run simulations of experiences its owner has had (much like playing a video game in the mind) in order to understand new things and get ready for action in the world...People learn (academic and non-academic) specialist languages and their concomitant ways of thinking best when they can tie words and structures of those languages to experiences they have had--experiences with which they can build [mental] simulations to prepare themselves for action in the domains in which the specialist language is used (e.g. biology or video games)” (qtd. in Klopfer, p. 175).

- the work of David Shaffer, especially *How Computer Games Help Children Learn* (2006) and the role of** epistemic frames**. Shaffer writes that “the work of creative professionals is organized around epistemic frames: collections of skills, knowledge, identities, values, and epistemologies that professionals use to think in innovative ways,” and that “innovators learn these epistemic frames through professional training that is very different from traditional academic classrooms because innovative thinking means more than just knowing the right answers on a test. It means having real-world skills, high standards, and professional values, and a particular way of thinking about problems and justifying solutions” (2006).

Ludic pedagogy has the potential to help students develop such epistemic frames in unique ways, not just in the language arts, but across disciplines. As faculty, and as an institution of higher education, we have the responsibility and opportunity to develop innovative curricula that introduces, reinforces, integrates and assesses these epistemic frames, including discrete course objectives as well as larger program objectives, graduation competencies, and workforce needs. This curricula need not come in the form of mass market software, but can be designed to meet specific institutional goals, course objectives and student/faculty interest.

Take for example the project “world without oil”—a collaborative simulation of a global oil shortage developed by Independent Television Services. ITVS created an alternative reality “game” in which 1800 players from across the globe helped shape content, chronicling an “accelerated time” energy crisis via blogs, videos, voicemail and photos ([http://www.worldwithoutoil.org](http://www.worldwithoutoil.org/metahome.htm)). Guided by developers’ architecture and narrative, the rich, user-generated context of the simulation challenged players to “Play it—before you live it” and to discover workable solutions to specific problems.

Simulations like these provide exciting opportunities for interdisciplinary collaboration and integrated, experiential learning, with great potential for learning community programming in particular. By incorporating real data into such simulations (student demographics, federal aid for public higher education, Bureau of Labor Statistics, etc.), there is great potential for students to simultaneously develop relevant epistemic frames (not only seeing through discipline specific lenses, but acting according to the guiding principles and discourse of that field), while potentially problem-solving for the greater needs of the institution and community.

- the work of Jane McGonigal (e.g. *World Without Oil* and *Super Better*), author of *Reality Is Broken* and Director of Games Research & Development at the [Institute for the Future](http://avantgame.com/iftf.org). I am most interested in applying foundational principles from McGonigal’s massive-multiplayer **alternative reality games** to the design of problem-based learning activities and crowdsourced collaborative learning. The Alternate Reality Game (ARG) Creation Workshop I attended as part of the Independent Activities Period at MIT (January 30--February 3, 2012) helped provide a launching point for this work, as did exploring MIT’s Education Arcade ARG Project *Vanished *and collaborating with Scott Nicholson and the MIT Library Advisory Council to build an orientation ARG prototype. 

Jay Johnson’s (2012) paper [“This is Not a Game: Alternate Reality Games as a First Year Composition Course Structure”](http://impovart.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Jay-Johnson-GLS8-This-is-Not-a-Game.pdf) provides a compelling look at the potential of ARGs through the lens of constructivist theory, composition theory, and transmedia theory. “The ARG is,” according to Johnson, “by definition, reliant on community participation (or, ‘a social system’), which makes it particularly suited to a composition classroom concerned with creating a space for multiple interpretations.” Further, “the group formation, sharing, and negotiation of interpretations can be encouraged, even required, by the game's structure,” where “as players solve interpretive puzzles, their moves are incorporated into the evolution of the game, often prompting the direction of the next challenge issued. In other words, players themselves dictate the course of the game. (...) Thus, the ARG structure can also help students to become—and, importantly, see themselves as—autonomous learners” (p. 3).

I am particularly interested in the promise of ARGs for examining the rhetorical situation, visual rhetoric and visual literacy, digital literacy, stasis theory, collective intelligence, affinity spaces and epistemic frames. 

- As a result of my sabbatical, I’ve also developed an interest in 

- ludonarrative consonance and dissonance; 

- games as an art form; 

- literary criticism of video games; 

- and critical differences between commercial and educational games (and why this is problematic). 

**The Xenos-ISLE Project at LGN**

The most significant unanticipated development of my sabbatical has been my invitation to collaborate with the Learning Games Network to develop the Xenos-ISLE game for Spanish speaking adults learning English. This partnership has provided me with valuable working experience, from task-based language acquisition theory to game design principles and mechanics. 

In January, 2012, my work at LGN focused on establishing and refining a language learning curriculum framework with ESL Specialist Amabel Luers. I also worked closely with Executive Director Alex Chisholm and Data Architect Maria Saiz on the Global Learning Objects database design on a new learning objectives framework to map player activity in games though both stealth (database) and transparent (dashboard) assessment. The new GLO database structure includes both a language proficiency-based framework (based on the Illinois ESL Content Standards) and a task-based framework (based on the theoretical models of David Nunan in *Task-based Language Teaching*, 2004). Also valuable to my thinking about task-based language theory were:

- *A Framework for the Implementation of Task-based Instruction* (Peter Skehan, 1995);

- *The Cognition Hypothesis, Task Design and Adult Task-Based Language Learning *(Peter Robinson, 2003);

- “You’re Not Studying, You’re Just Playing that Sims™ Game of Yours” (Ravi Purushotma, 2005).

- “Principles of Instructed Language Learning” (Rod Ellis, 2005), especially Ellis’ notions of: 

- delayed grammar instruction in favor of building formulaic chunks;

- emphasis on pragmatic, contextualized meaning over semantic meaning;

- intrinsic motivation though authentic contexts and tasks; 

- developing implicit knowledge through plentiful communicative practice; 

- eliciting production of “free constructed responses” through communicative tasks. (2005)

Ellis provides an approach to task-based language learning that is largely consistent with the Xenos-ISLE approach, and his work played a key role in the LGN team’s preliminary adoption of David Nunan’s task-based framework for mapping cognitive, interpersonal, linguistic, affective and creative schema to individual games within the Xenos world.

In February, 2012 at LGN I began to map the task-based framework (Nunan) and explicit language standards (Illinois) to existing Xenos games (Maildrop, Rails, Empty-Handed, Triangulate, Glyphs and Word Scrambler), to layer Nunan & Illinois to the Xenos curriculum framework, and to conduct a needs assessment of Xenos games and activities against the curriculum framework. At this time I also began collaborating with LGN co-founder Scot Osterweil and game designer Dan Roy on the Xenos game storyline, and produced a draft of the arrival scene and metanarrative. 

In March, 2012 at LGN I began to playtest Xenos games designed by Filament Games and The Super Group to prioritize core target proficiencies for the beginner/low intermediate learning path and identifying language learning needs for the Gates grant target users. I continued to collaborate with ESL Specialist Amabel Luers to match Xenos games and activities to learning path modules. 

In April, 2012 at LGN I took a leading role in developing two new games, from concept to paper prototype. Loteria for Xenos is a variation of the traditional Mexican game. Instead of operating by chance, players in the Xenos game listen to audio clues describing pictograms on their board and play a strategic game against other players to complete a predetermined pattern. In Driving Me Bananas (working title), a driver and navigator communicate through VOIP (Voice Over Internet) to travel through an expanded version of the Xenos world, strategizing to accomplish short term and long term goals and respond to real-time conditions in a dynamic environment. In April we also met and playtested with English language learners at the Dudley Literacy Center in Roxbury who will be participating in the fall pre-pilot. 

In May, 2012, I collaborated with the LGN team to develop and playtest new game designs, to identify custom data sets for games, and to document and prioritize game mechanic modifications for existing games. A significant focus of this work involves leveling (primarily based on custom data sets and game mechanics) and sequencing of games and activities along the learning path modules. I contributed design work primarily for Loteria, Driving Me Bananas, Empty Handed, Breaking News, Tale Spin--including story archive, Blurbs, In Other Words, Xenos Cache, and InTense. I also visited Filament Games in Madison, Wisconsin in May for a Xenos-ISLE game design jam with Creative Director Dan Norton, Chief Technical Officer Alex Stone and Learning Games Network game designer Dan Roy.

I have been hired by LGN to continue working part-time on the Xenos-ISLE project and other projects beyond my sabbatical. 

I can’t overstate how transformative my experience at the Learning Games Network has been. 

- In helping to build Xenos-ISLE, I’ve enjoyed exploring the relationship between language learning theory and principles of play. There are many interesting problems and possibilities for how in-game assessment informs game play, and how learning in games transfers to life outside the game--not only learning about language, but seeing language as playful, cooperative, and imperfect.

- My work at LGN has also allowed me to think like a designer and to gain a greater respect for and understanding of elegant design, intuitive mechanics, and meaningful play experience. Not only is this thinking *relevant *to curriculum design for the classroom, it is absolutely *necessary*. Thinking as designers is also critical for students as active producers, not consumers, of knowledge, and the process of design-thinking allows students the opportunity for embodied, contextualized learning through various epistemic frames. 

- Collaborating with LGN (and the greater learning games, serious games, games for change community) has shown me firsthand the value of social media for professional development. At the MIT Sandbox Summit and Games + Learning + Society Conference, much of the audience was actively Tweeting away key quotes and thoughts in response to speakers, crowdsourcing notes in a collaborative Google Doc, posting video feeds and links and other relevant resources, and engaging with colleagues across the globe who were livestreaming events to their computers and phones and iPads (as I later did with the Games for Change and ISTE Conferences). Participating in this community, I see the power of social networking systems as means of curation and connection in an increasingly crowded information space. I am also beginning to view technology in the classroom (e.g., bring-your-own-device) less as a distraction and more as opportunity for engagement...hotspots for research, crowdsourcing, collaborative design and learning. 

Many thanks to Alex Chisholm and Scot Osterweil for bringing me on board, and to Amabel Luers, Dan Roy, Michael Suen, Christine Chiang, Maria Saiz, Peter Sidwell, Jennifer Groff, and Heather deManbey for their insight, creativity and playfulness. 

**(c) An appraisal of the relationship between the results obtained and those anticipated in the sabbatical leave program statement.**

I couldn’t be more pleased with my sabbatical in terms of the experience of the sabbatical itself and the opportunities that I now have to transform my curriculum and participate as an active member of the learning games movement.

First, I’ll directly address the four primary goals I established in my sabbatical proposal. 

- to study emerging learning science theories of digital literacy and effective gaming learning principles (beginning with the work of Gee, Selfe & Hawisher, Shaffer, and Squire);

I am very satisfied with the breadth and depth of the study I conducted during my sabbatical through literature review, hands-on game development at the Learning Games Network, and connecting to the learning games community through LGN/MIT partnerships, conferences and social media. (Sections a and b of this report address this research specifically.) 

- to follow this research by surveying current, relevant applications of gaming models in educational settings (beginning with projects by MIT’s Education Arcade, The Games for Learning Institute, and The Institute for the Future);

The serendipitous partnership I developed with LGN provided me with more than I could have hoped for with the Xenos-ISLE Project. An interesting aspect of the Gates Grant funding this phase of the project is its mission to connect with adult language learners through workplaces and libraries. This project has given me greater perspective of adult language learners outside the community college system, and how task-based, situated, playful learning--and learning through games--might serve adult language learners within the community college system as well. 

My study of games created by the MIT Education Arcade (i.e. *Lure of the Labyrinth* and *Vanished*) and the work of the Institute for the Future (i.e. *World Without Oil* and *SuperBetter*) showed me potential for learning games played largely outside the classroom, though certainly there is significant (and often built-in) means of building these games into a curriculum. 

Kurt Squire’s work (especially *Changing the Game: What Happens When Video Games Enter the Classroom?*, 2005) provided me with the clearest sense of the possibilities for playing video games *in *the classroom itself, though I got the most leverage rethinking my curriculum from Squire’s work on design thinking and systems thinking. Squire’s work was absolutely critical in this process, leading me to step back from course outcomes, program outcomes, graduation competencies and communication standards to identify, among others: the rhetorical situation, visual rhetoric and visual literacy, digital literacy, stasis theory, collective intelligence, affinity spaces and epistemic frames. 

It’s worth noting that the scope of my research was broad, and this was necessary in order for me to establish a foundation for meaningfully understanding playful learning and design thinking. I am very much interested in continuing to research, and to contribute to, ludic pedagogy in post-secondary composition and literature curricula, especially for learners in community colleges and learners in remedial courses. 

- to prepare for publication a paper on the application of gaming theory in post-secondary language arts curriculum;

During the course of my sabbatical I have identified the following areas of interest for academic writing:

- Systemic thinking and design thinking in the two-year college composition course;

- Affinity spaces and epistemic frames in the two-year college composition course;

- Ludic pedagogy and the role of narrative in the course-hosted ARG;

- Ludonarrative consonance and dissonance: *Bioshock* as a playable critique of Ayn Rand’s Objectivism; 

- *Journey* as proof-of-concept for narrative and communicative multi-play without language;

- Meaningful assessment through gameplay?: the relationship between task-based game progress and the mastery of discrete proficiencies. 

I do not have plans to prepare a paper for publication in the immediate future. I feel that I may have the theoretical wherewithal to do so at this point, but would find it far more meaningful to reflect on theory in practice as a result of my curriculum redesign for the fall 2012 semester and beyond.

- to use my findings to rethink the way I teach language arts in post-secondary education, with potential results ranging from an initial single assignment or unit, to a paradigm shift in my approach to teaching and learning with available and emerging technologies.

There are a number of ways to incorporate ludic pedagogy into post-secondary language arts curriculum. 

One way is by playing digital games in the classroom, or by making digital games central to the curriculum, in order to give learners the opportunity for embodied learning and systems thinking. As Squire says, “This *systemic *thinking is valuable because it helps people solve problems holistically, rather than focusing on single cause solutions...Systemic thinking isn’t valued much inside schools today (particularly because it isn’t captured easily by standardized tests), but this type of thinking is important everywhere outside school, from ecology to engineering to politics” (5). Squire explores this model in his 2011 book, especially through his work with Civilization. 

In the coming semester, I do not plan to include digital gameplay as part of the curriculum, but I will incorporate ludic pedagogy and the learning principles and theory explored in section b of this report. In this section of my report, I will outline specific activities and practices I plan to implement as early as the coming semester as the result of my sabbatical experience. 

- ***Weekly spontaneous writing prompts conducted following the Amherst Writers ******&****** Artists method for leading writing workshops. ***

Pat Schneider (2003) describes the AWA method in *Writing Alone and with Others*, including these** **Five Essential Practices:

 

- *A nonhierarchical spirit (how we treat writing) in the workshop is maintained while at the same time an appropriate discipline (how we interact as a group) keeps writers safe.*

- *All writing is treated as fiction unless the writer requests that it be treated as autobiography. At all times writers are free to refrain from reading their work aloud.*

- *Absolutely no criticism, suggestion, or question is directed toward the writer in response to first-draft, just written work. A thorough critique is offered only when the writer asks for it and distributes work in manuscript form. Critique is balanced; there is as much affirmation as suggestion for change.*

- *The teaching of craft is taken seriously and is conducted through exercises that invite experimentation and growth as well as through response to manuscripts in private conferences.*

- *The leader writes along with the participants and reads that work aloud at least once in each writing session. This practice is absolutely necessary, for only in this way is there equality of risk-taking and mutuality of trust.* (Schneider, 2003)

The AWA method is well-suited to fostering the kind of learning environment that Osterweil (2008) describes in the Four Freedoms: the freedom to experiment, the freedom to fail, the freedom to take on new identities, and the freedom of effort. Additionally, writers have the opportunity to receive immediate feedback on their work from both instructor and peers (“amplified feedback principle”; Gee, 2007), feedback that by the nature of the AWA method encourages a “psychosocial moratorium” (Gee, 2007) and an understanding of writing as an iterative process. 

- ***Situated learning through design thinking***

Instead of “frontloading” instruction that addresses rhetorical situations, I intend to promote learning by doing through a number of activities that ask students to act as designers. 

- **interactive storytelling**: No Crusts Interactive provided a model for the kind of design work I’d like to do with students in their Sandbox Summit workshop *Once Upon A Time: Writing Children’s Games Isn’t Just Mechanics *(2012), where participants were asked to identify key narrative elements from a children’s story (e.g., “Little Red Riding Hood”) and key functionality from a given device (e.g.,. the iPhone 4S) to design a multimedia storytelling application. In such as activity, student-designers might, for example, identify Riding Hood’s passage through the forest as an important exploration activity, and might imagine using the iPhone touch screen and motion sensor functionalities to allow for the “picking” of raspberries, the “blowing” of dandelions, the “shaking” of trees for fruit, the built-in compass for navigation, etc.

This kind of design thinking requires learners to read closely and think critically about a text, to consider the needs of an audience and the possibilities of textual interaction (the affordances of the device), and to work collaboratively to develop a blueprint for synthesizing form and content. 

- **game design**: No Crusts Interactive also provided me with practical models for design thinking in their Sandbox Summit Workshop *Playing with Your Head: Deconstructing Gaming Psychobabble*, led by Carla Engelbrecht Fisher. In one model, a facilitator asks groups to identify a domain or discipline around which participants will design a game concept, then to imagine how an *existing *game might be used to teach principles within that domain or discipline. Using the formula “It’s like X, but teaches Y,” participants might say, for example, “It’s like the game Clue, but teaches Rules of Evidence for Criminal Justice. Next, the designers must identify a methodology for effectively conveying the game’s learning goals, using the formula: “It’s like X, but teaches Y and it has Z” (where Z might be, for example, problem-based learning, collaborative play, real-time feedback, etc). Participants might say, “It’s like the game Clue, but teaches Rules of Evidence and uses real case studies.”

	

A design process such as this, using learning goals of a given curriculum, requires students to think about key principles as a producer, not just a consumer, of knowledge. At the same time, exploring methodology allows students to learn about learning in an applied activity rather than as abstract theory.

- ***Playing Metagame (and redesigning content and mechanics) ***[^c6][^c7]

The Metagame, as its inventors Local No. 12 say, “is a game about aesthetics, and playing well requires cultural literacy, strategic thinking, and social negotiation skills” (Local No. 12, 2011, p. 6).

In a nutshell, players are given a hand of cards from a thematic deck (I’ll be using the Culture edition, initially, and then a custom deck). The cards include content cards (i.e Tupperware, Barney, and To Kill a Mockingbird) and comparison cards (i.e. “Which reminds us more of our humanity?,” “Which deserves more respect than it gets?” and “Which better explains a generation?”). There are many variations, but essentially, players are asked a comparison question and then choose one of the content cards from their hand to make a pitch for, for example, why Tupperware better explains a generation than To Kill a Mockingbird.

I intend to play the Metagame, initially, as is, as a way of exploring argument and values and fostering a collaborative learning environment. Then, I plan to introduce custom wild cards that will ask players, for example to make their case through *ethos,* *pathos *or *logos*; to reach consensus through Rogerian argument; or to focus their argument to appeal to a 3rd grader. 

							[http://www.metaga.me/](http://www.metaga.me/)

Next, I’d like players to create their own custom cards (both content cards and comparison cards). The first round of designs could be group designs, adding culture cards to the existing deck. Another round of designs could ask students to identify cards that represent key aspects of their particular field of interest (semiotic domain, affinity space, etc.) and to work with small groups to develop meaningful questions and art. I’ll also invite students to design their own game mechanics that lend themselves to the content they’ve developed. Not only can this kind of activity be geared towards any discipline or topic, but the product of the design work results in a sharable, playable game that can further the exploration of diverse domains using argument, systems thinking, authentic rhetorical situations, public speaking, group work, etc. 

- ***Designing a grading system that encourages experimentation, collaboration, and ******creativity.***

During my sabbatical I’ve engaged in broad dialogue about “gamification” trends in business, marketing, social networking, education, etc., where gamification means adapting game mechanics (badges, points, power-ups, etc.) to achieve an ends in superficial ways (“points”-ification; Nicholson, 2012) that fail to maintain the essence of games as interesting challenges. In education, too, it seems somewhat problematic that traditional percentage-based grading systems are deficit based, meaning that a student who gets a 70% on a first assignment worth 30% of her grade can no longer achieve a grade higher than 91% in the course. While this system seems a reasonable method for assuring that overall grades reflect learning objective achievement *as assessed*, and for maintaining the standards of a course, an instructor, a department, an institution, a state, etc., this system, too, relies to an extent on “points”-ification, and does not seem well-designed for fostering risk-taking and the kind of creative thinking demanded by contemporary work and life.

I intend to experiment with a grading system that maintains a rubric-based letter/number grade for individual assignments, while offering students greater choices of assignment types and the ability to offset low or mediocre grades in some assignments with alternative/additional assignments that meet the same or similar learning objectives. I’m interested in the kind of model that Professor Barry Fishman (2012) uses in his [*Videogames and Learning*](http://www-personal.umich.edu/~fishman/games/ED222_Grading.pdf) course at the University of Michigan (with the support of a teaching team). 

A revised grading system, may include some of the following options: 

**Essays **Required (by course description...for now!)

- Essay 1: 20 points (previously 10%) 

- Essay 2: 20 points (previously 10%) 

- Essay 3: 20 points (previously 10%) 

- Essay 4: 20 points (previously 10%)

**Reading Journals**

- Unit X: 3 points ea/up to 18 points per unit (previously 10% total)

- Unit Y: 3 points ea/up to 18 points per unit (previously 10% total)

- Unit Z: 3 points ea/up to 18 points per unit (previously 10% total)

- **Option**: student-curated, annotated resources; student-created design sites to support the unit; student-generated reading questions, etc. [points TBD]

**Presentations **(previously 10%):

- small group prep activity: [pecha-kucha](http://www.pecha-kucha.org/) (20 slides/20 seconds each) trial run **OR** poster session 10 points

- pecha-kucha **OR **poster session** **20 points

**Class Participation**: (previously 10%)

In general, I intend to design a system that encourages student collaboration and peer support, including: 

- crowdsourcing to build student resources (i.e. class notes on shared Google Doc); 

- active course Tweeting;

- Team reward system: all drafts on time, all members comment on a draft, etc [cumulative up to 30 points]

- Attendance: 2 points per class/up to 60 points 

**Mechanics**

Quizzes: (previously 10%, best 4 of 5 on Blackboard, retake once okay). 

Revise so that points = % of total score (i.e. 5 quizzes x 100% = 500; 5% of 500 = up to 25 points (unlimited retakes until deadline)

**Option: OR **make your own mechanics resource for students, a team project up to 25 points

**Be Creative! (Power-ups)**

**Choose one option:**

- Turn an in-class writing exercise into a longer, crafted work 15 points

- Participate in [National Novel Writing Month](http://www.nanowrimo.org/en/about/whatisnano). 15,000 words = 15 points; 25,000 words = 25 points; 50,000 words = 50 points

- Design a game that teaches core learning objectives (design documents and playable paper prototype): 25 points

	

	*Total points so far = 279 (total excluding power-ups)*	

*So, for example: *

*A*	*=*	*265 *

*A-*	*=*	*257*

*B+*	*=*	*246*

*B*	*=*	*237*

